30 days until i leave pittsford.  i got my roomie/room in the mail last week.  i've already began to pack too. i have two boxes all ready to go.  i bought most of my dorm stuff, i have yet to get a fridge, vacuum, and some fall/winter clothes. i can't believe it's almost here.  one more month, and i am out of here until thanksgiving.   its gonna be hard to say goodbye.

my friday before grad was amazing. i went to canadaigua to see max and we spent most of the day together at his house next to the lake.  then when i went to work, mrs kelly came and visited and tipped me (as a hostess) which was the best thing ever.  it is so beautiful out, and today is our big day. congratulations sutherland 07. we made it!

The day has finally come,
for us to cry and cheer.
To leave these halls forever
with lots of tears.
These twelve years have gone by so fast
along with classes we thought would always last.
But now as we say goodbye,
the time here has flown by.
The teachers here taught us all we could be taught
From the ABC's and 123's
to learning all we can be.
They have touched our hearts,
but now its time to leave,
to be taught by new teachers,
along with some preachers.
As we think back we remember all of the memories
of classes and teachers,
of friends sitting in the bleachers.
But now as we receive our diplomas and say goodbye,
Reality sets in that we are finally leaving.
We knew this day would come,
but it always seemed far away in the future.
As we walk out these doors and leave for home,
Possibly never seeing anybody again,
We'll remember the memories,
and how we'll always have them.
my senior year was definitely not what i expected.

"To let go isn't to forget, not to think about, or ignore. It doesn't leave feelings of anger, jealousy, or regret. Letting go isn't about winning or losing. It's not about pride and it's not about how you appear, and it's not obsessing or dwelling on the past. Letting go isn't blocking memories or thinking sad thoughts, and doesn't leave emptiness, hurt, or sadness. It's not about giving in or giving up. Letting go isn't about loss and it's not about defeat. Letting go is learning and experiencing and growing. It's about all that you have, all that you had, and all that you will have. Letting go is having the courage to accept change, and the strength to keep moving. To let go is to understand."

so i've decided i have really poor anger management skills.  you know those moments you're so mad you just want to punch/break something, then you realize there's nothing to break without severe consequences so you attempt to release your anger in other forms? like maybe taking a long run or going out for a walk but then you realize there's nowhere to go.  then maybe option 3 is yelling at someone who won't yell back at you. but that's often rare finding someone who would do that.  i think that's how i handle anger. first i'd like to break something, then i'd like to do something physical, and that doesn't work i'll yell. really loud. 

emotions suck.

Ask the 25 year old who tried to electrocute himself.
he lived. but both of his arms are gone. 
What about jumping? Ask John. He used to be intelligent,
with an ingaging sense of humor. That was before he leapt
from a building. Now, he`s brain-damaged, & will always
need care. He staggers & has seizures. He lives in a fog. But
worst of all, he knows he used to be normal. 

What about pills? Ask the 12 year old with extensive liver
damage from an overdose. Have you ever seen someone
die with liver damage? It's a hard way to go.. 
What about a gun? Ask the 24 year old who shot himself
in the head. Now he drags one leg, has a useless arm, and
has no vision or hearing on one side. He lived through his
"fool-proof" suicide. You might, too. 
What about crashing a car? Ask the 16 year old who drove
his mother's car into a telephone pole, trying to kill himself &
his best friend, as part of a suicide pact. Now he sits in jail,
sentanced to 15 years, for his best friends murder.

But.. who will clean your blood off of the carpet? Or scrape
your brains off of the ceiling? Commercial cleaning companies
may refuse that job, but someone has to do it..
Who will have to cut you down from where you
hung yourself or identify your bloated body after you`ve
drowned? Your father? Your mother? Your wife?
Your son? The carefully worded loving suicide note is of
no help. Those who loved you will never completely
recover. They`ll feel regret, & an un-ending pain.
Suicide is contagious. Look around you family.
Look closely at the 4 year old playing with his cars on the
rug. Kill yourself tonight, & he may do it 10 years from now.
You do have other choices. There are people who can help
you through this crisis. Call a hotline. Call a friend. Call your
minister or priest. Call a doctor or a hospital. Call the police.
They will tell you that there's hope. Maybe you'll find it in the
mail tomorrow; or in a phone call this weekend. But what
you`re seeking could just be a minute, a month, or a day away.

REMEMBER; SUiCiDE iS A PERMANENT SOLUTiON TO
A TEMPORARY PROBLEM.
